{
  "result": "At dawn, the city feels like a stage between rehearsals. Delivery trucks whisper at curbs, pigeons hold committee meetings on power lines, and windows glow one by one as if someone is testing stars before release. I like walking then, before headlines harden and notifications start tugging at sleeves. Morning has a democratic silence: the baker dusting flour, the nurse ending a night shift, the student cramming definitions on the bus all move through the same pale light.\n\nLately I\u2019ve been thinking about attention as a kind of currency. We spend it carelessly on outrage, shiny trivialities, and arguments we never meant to join. Meanwhile, small riches wait in plain sight: the way rain darkens brick, the patience of houseplants leaning toward a single bright square, the half-second before laughter when everyone inhales together. None of these moments trend. They simply occur, quietly offering to make a life feel inhabited.\n\nIf I had to choose one ambition, it would be this: to become reliable at noticing. Noticing when someone is tired behind a practiced smile. Noticing when my own certainty grows loud and brittle. Noticing the ordinary miracles that ask nothing except witness. Maybe wisdom is less about finding grand answers and more about returning, again and again, to what is already here\u2014warm coffee, honest work, a friend\u2019s voice saying, \u201cI\u2019m listening.\u201d\n\nTomorrow the noise will return, of course, but I hope to carry this discipline into it, spending attention like a gardener, watering what grows and letting weeds pass.",
